            <h2>Iriga City</h2>
            <h3>City of Crystal Clear Springs</h3>
            <hr>
            <img src="<?= $this->webroot ?>theme/weatherph/img/tourism/irigaCity1.png" alt="">

            <p>Iriga City is the economic, educational and cultural center of the 5th District of Camarines Sur. Its most prominent natural land- mark, Mt. Asog, with its volcanic soil, made it one of the biggest abaca producing areas in Bicol during the Spanish and American occupation. During pre-colonial times, the mountain was the center of a first-harvest offering ritual, celebrated today as the Tinagba festival.</p>
            <p>Iriga is also the birthplace of the country’s first bus transporta- tion company, the ALATCO, which along with the three schools established in the post-war years, propelled the progress of the town. In 1968, Iriga was converted into a component city.</p>
            <p>Iriga City is a dynamic and progressive city. It has posted an average of 11.3% annual growth over the last seven years. Its advocacy on good governance earned it the 2009 Excellence in Good Governance Award from the Department of Interior and Local Government - Region V and a citation as one of the Top 10 Performing local governments in the country in 2010.</p>
            <p>Iriga City envisions a vibrant economy and a contented life for every Irigueno through a transparent local government unit, a strong agroecotourism backbone and a people with a deep sense of pride, identity, shared values and character.</p>
            <p>The City is also called the City of Crystal Clear Springs, boasting with more than 30 natural springs that provide a rich source of drinking and irrigation waters. The City is located at the heart of Bicol Economic Growth Corridor. It is also known as the Character City with its warm and friendly, honest and industrious inhabitants.</p>
            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>
            <ol>
                <li>1. February 11 in time for the Tinagba Festival as it lures the visitor to a cultural experience which is the reenactment of an old pagan ritual of offering and thanksgiving. The whole day merrymaking includes a day parade of colored bull carts that are laden with the best products of the farm followed by revelers in colored costumes in a street dance around the city.</li>
                <li>2. June 13 is the City Fiesta in honor of its patron, St. Anthony of Padua. It is highlighted with the coronation of Ms. Iriga, Ms. Rinconada and Ms. Bicol Tourism.</li>
                <li>3. September 3 is the City’s foundation anniversary with a grand military parade whose participation and competition is open to all not limited only to the two big universities and col- leges and all other schools in the City but also to the neighbor- ing academic institutions in the neighboring municipalities. The Sumagang Awards, the highest civilian award is being conferred to outstanding Irigueños during the City’s foundation day.</li>
            </ol>

