            <h3>Iriga City’s Must Do List</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>1. Climb any of the following: The over-100 step Grotto of Our Lady of Lourdes built atop the Calvario Hill that faces Mount Iriga offering a bird’s eye view of the City’s central business district; Mount Iriga which rises some 4,823 feet above sea level. Its climb is challenging. Its cold surrounding makes a fitting habitat for wild berries and local specie of pine calleda agoho; and the Inorogan Shrine, on top of a hill at Barangay Sto. Domingo. The Pieta shrine was built to commemorate the miraculous escape from death and destruction of the inhabitants from the eruption of Mount Iriga in the 30s.</li>
                <li>2. Taste Iriga’s delicacies. Gulay na katnga (laing), tinutktok, pili nut candies, santan, and the special Iriga Bicol express. These products are available at the Katnga Center located at the ground floor of the old City Hall. Native products and souvenir items are sold at the Pasalubong Center at the ground floor of the Iriga Public Market. Dine also at Mariolis, Desny Grill, Mayees All Chinese Restaurant. MCM Restaurant, Biggs Diner, and Crown Park Restaurant.</li>
                <li>3. Visit the Gawad Kalinga Character Village located at Barangay Perpetual Help. Its 140 beautiful and multi-colored houses which make up a sustainable community development project of Iriga City government and the GK Community Development Foundation is a major tourist attraction.</li>
                <li>4. Visit the Iriga Government Center, a modern edifice that is fully air-conditioned. Painted in Mediterranean-inspired col- ors, it brings together all the important offices in one central location to facilitate the processing of documents and other transactions. Visit also the New Iriga Public Library which is fully air conditioned and operates daily from 8:00 am to 8:00 pm except Sunday. A Nora Aunor corner is a major interest to many. Visit and shop at the Iriga Public Market, the cleanest in the region where you can find fast food chains, native products and food and just everything that suits your fancy.</li>
                <li>5. Watch the Tinagba Festival on February 11 and enjoy the parade of bullcarts laden with fresh farm products and the streetdancing of revelers in their beautiful costumes. Watch the Coronation Night of Ms Iriga/Ms Rinconada/Ms Bicol Tourism. During your free time side – trip and enjoy a dip at Masuso, Crystal, Cascade and Fountain Spring Resorts.</li>
            </ol>

